# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wireless-mbus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] AMR technologies include handheld, mobile and network technologies based on telephony platforms (wired and wireless), radio frequency (RF), or powerline transmission.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] With touch-based AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer or data collection device with a wand or probe.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The device automatically collects the readings from a meter by touching or placing the read probe close to a reading coil enclosed in the touchpad.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] When a button is pressed, the probe sends an interrogate signal to the touch module to collect the meter reading.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The software in the device matches the serial number to one in the route database, and saves the meter reading for later download to a billing or data collection computer.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Since the meter reader still has to go to the site of the meter, this is sometimes referred to as "on-site" AMR.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Another form of contact reader uses a standardized infrared port to transmit data.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Protocols are standardized between manufacturers by such documents as ANSI C12.18 or IEC 61107.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] AMR hosting is a back-office solution which allows a user to track their electricity, water, or gas consumption over the Internet.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] All data is collected in near real-time, and is stored in a database by data acquisition software.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The user can view the data via a web application, and can analyze the data using various online analysis tools such as charting load profiles, analyzing tariff components, and verify their utility bill.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Radio frequency based AMR can take many forms.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The more common ones are handheld, mobile, satellite and fixed network solutions.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] There are both two-way RF systems and one-way RF systems in use that use both licensed and unlicensed RF bands.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In a two-way or "wake up" system, a radio signal is normally sent to an AMR meter's unique serial number, instructing its transceiver to power-up and transmit its data.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The meter transceiver and the reading transceiver both send and receive radio signals.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In a one-way "bubble-up" or continuous broadcast type system, the meter transmits continuously and data is sent every few seconds.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This means the reading device can be a receiver only, and the meter a transmitter only.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Data travels only from the meter transmitter to the reading receiver.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] There are also hybrid systems that combine one-way and two-way techniques, using one-way communication for reading and two-way communication for programming functions.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] RF-based meter reading usually eliminates the need for the meter reader to enter the property or home, or to locate and open an underground meter pit.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The utility saves money by increased speed of reading, has less liability from entering private property, and has fewer missed readings from being unable to access the meter.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The technology based on RF is not readily accepted everywhere.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In several Asian countries, the technology faces a barrier of regulations in place pertaining to use of the radio frequency of any radiated power.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] For example, in India the radio frequency which is generally in ISM band is not free to use even for low power radio of 10 mW.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The majority of manufacturers of electricity meters have radio frequency devices in the frequency band of 433/868 MHz for large scale deployment in European countries.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The frequency band of 2.4 GHz can be now used in India for outdoor as well as indoor applications, but few manufacturers have shown products within this frequency band.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Initiatives in radio frequency AMR in such countries are being taken up with regulators wherever the cost of licensing outweighs the benefits of AMR.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In handheld AMR, a meter reader carries a handheld computer with a built-in or attached receiver/transceiver (radio frequency or touch) to collect meter readings from an AMR capable meter.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This is sometimes referred to as "walk-by" meter reading since the meter reader walks by the locations where meters are installed as they go through their meter reading route.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Handheld computers may also be used to manually enter readings without the use of AMR technology as an alternate but this will not support exhaustive data which can be accurately read using the meter reading electronically.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Mobile or "drive-by" meter reading is where a reading device is installed in a vehicle.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The meter reader drives the vehicle while the reading device automatically collects the meter readings.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Often, for mobile meter reading, the reading equipment includes navigational and mapping features provided by GPS and mapping software.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] With mobile meter reading, the reader does not normally have to read the meters in any particular route order, but just drives the service area until all meters are read.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Components often consist of a laptop or proprietary computer, software, RF receiver/transceiver, and external vehicle antennas.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Transmitters for data collection satellites can be installed in the field next to existing meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The satellite AMR devices communicate with the meter for readings, and then sends those readings over a fixed or mobile satellite network.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This network requires a clear view to the sky for the satellite transmitter/receiver, but eliminates the need to install fixed towers or send out field technicians, thereby being particularly suited for areas with low geographic meter density.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] There are also meters using AMR with RF technologies such as cellular phone data systems, Zigbee, Bluetooth, Wavenis and others.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Federal Communications Commission (FCC) licensed frequencies and others under FCC Part 15, which allows use of unlicensed radio frequencies.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] WiSmart is a versatile platform which can be used by a variety of electrical home appliances in order to provide wireless TCP/IP communication using the 802.11 b/g protocol.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Devices such as the Smart Thermostat permit a utility to lower a home's power consumption to help manage power demand.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The city of Corpus Christi became one of the first cities in the United States to implement citywide Wi-Fi, which had been free until May 31, 2007, mainly to facilitate AMR after a meter reader was attacked by a dog.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Today many meters are designed to transmit using Wi-Fi, even if a Wi-Fi network is not available, and they are read using a drive-by local Wi-Fi hand held receiver.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The meters installed in Corpus Christi are not directly Wi-Fi enabled, but rather transmit narrow-band burst telemetry on the 460 MHz band.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This narrow-band signal has much greater range than Wi-Fi, so the number of receivers required for the project are far fewer.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Special receiver stations then decode the narrow-band signals and resend the data via Wi-Fi.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Most of the automated utility meters installed in the Corpus Christi area are battery powered.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Wi-Fi technology is unsuitable for long-term battery-powered operation.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] PLC is a method where electronic data is transmitted over power lines back to the substation, then relayed to a central computer in the utility's main office.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This would be considered a type of fixed network system—the network being the distribution network which the utility has built and maintains to deliver electric power.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Such systems are primarily used for electric meter reading.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Some providers have interfaced gas and water meters to feed into a PLC type system.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In 1972, Theodore George "Ted" Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system which used digital transmission for security, fire and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities for all utilities.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This technology was a spin-off of the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as caller ID.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In 1974, Paraskevakos was awarded a U.S. patent for this technology.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first fully automated, commercially available remote meter reading and load management system.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Since this system was developed pre-Internet, Metretek utilized the IBM series 1 mini-computer.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] For this approach, Paraskevakos and Metretek were awarded multiple patents.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The primary driver for the automation of meter reading is not to reduce labor costs, but to obtain data that is difficult to obtain.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] As an example, many water meters are installed in locations that require the utility to schedule an appointment with the homeowner in order to obtain access to the meter.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In many areas, consumers have demanded that their monthly water bill be based on an actual reading, instead of (for example) an estimated monthly usage based on just one actual meter reading made every 12 months.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Early AMR systems often consisted of walk-by and drive-by AMR for residential customers, and telephone-based AMR for commercial or industrial customers.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] What was once a need for monthly data became a need for daily and even hourly readings of the meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Consequently, the sales of drive-by and telephone AMR has declined in the US, while sales of fixed networks has increased.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The trend now is to consider the use of advanced meters as part of an advanced metering infrastructure.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Originally AMR devices just collected meter readings electronically and matched them with accounts.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] As technology has advanced, additional data could then be captured, stored, and transmitted to the main computer, and often the metering devices could be controlled remotely.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] This can include events alarms such as tamper, leak detection, low battery, or reverse flow.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Many AMR devices can also capture interval data, and log meter events.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering infrastructure, or AMI is the new term coined to represent the networking technology of fixed network meter systems that go beyond AMR into remote utility management.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The meters in an AMI system are often referred to as smart meters, since they often can use collected data based on programmed logic.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The Automatic Meter Reading Association (AMRA) endorses the National Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners (NARUC) resolution to eliminate regulatory barriers to the broad implementation of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution, passed in February 2007, acknowledged the role of AMI in supporting the implementation of dynamic pricing and the resulting benefits to consumers.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution further identified the value of AMI in achieving significant utility operational cost savings in the areas of outage management, revenue protection and asset management.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The resolution also called for AMI business case analysis to identify cost-effective deployment strategies, endorsed timely cost recovery for prudently incurred AMI expenditures and made additional recommendations on rate making and tax treatment of such investments.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Advanced metering systems can provide benefits for utilities, retail providers and customers.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Benefits will be recognized by the utilities with increased efficiencies, outage detection, tamper notification and reduced labor cost as a result of automating reads, connections and disconnects.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Retail providers will be able to offer new innovative products in addition to customizing packages for their customers.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In addition, with the meter data being readily available, more flexible billing cycles would be available to their customers instead of following the standard utility read cycles.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] With timely usage information available to the customer, benefits will be seen through opportunities to manage their energy consumption and change from one REP to another with actual meter data.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Because of these benefits, many utilities are moving towards implementing some types of AMR solutions.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In many cases, smart metering is required by law (e.g.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the utility.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The benefits of smart metering for the customer.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Construction practices, weather, and the need for information drive utilities in different parts of the world towards AMR at different rates.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In the US, there have been significant fixed network deployments of both RF based and PLC based technologies.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] Some countries have either deployed or plan to deploy AMR systems throughout the entire country.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] By using a combination of AMR and energy analytics reports, SPAR were able to reduce energy consumption by 20%.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] AMI in Australia has grown from both government policy which sought to rectify observed market inefficiencies, and distribution businesses who looked to gain operational efficiencies.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In July 2008, there was a mandated program being planned in Victoria for the deployment of 2.6 million meters over a 4-year period.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The anticipated peak installation rate of AMI meters was 5,000 per day across Victoria.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] The program governance was provided by an industry steering committee.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] In 2009 the Victorian Auditor General undertook a review of the program and found that there were "significant inadequacies" in advice to Government and that project governance "has not been appropriate".
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] With the growing adoption of AMI meters and systems, AMR has been in decline in the U.S. electric utility sector.
[src:wireless-mbus/automatic-meter-reading] However, in the gas and water sectors, where it tends to be more expensive and complicated to replace meters, AMR remains prevalent, and some utilities continue to invest in new AMR meter deployments.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] A **short-range device** (**SRD**), described by ECC Recommendation 70-03, is a radio-frequency transmitter device used in telecommunication that has little capability of causing harmful interference to other radio equipment.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] Short-range devices are low-power transmitters, typically limited to 25–100 mW effective radiated power (ERP) or less, depending on the frequency band, which limits their useful range to a few hundred meters, which do not require licenses to use.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] Short-range wireless technologies include Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, NearLink, near-field communication (NFC), LPWAN, ultra-wideband (UWB) and IEEE 802.15.4.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] They are implemented by chips fabricated as RF CMOS integrated circuit (RF circuit).
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] As of 2009, short-range wireless chips ship approximately 1.7 billion units annually, with Bluetooth accounting for over 55% of shipments and Wi-Fi around 35% of shipments.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] The European Commission mandates through CEPT and ETSI the allocation of several device bands for these purposes, restricts the parameters of their use, and provides guidelines for avoiding radio interference.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] 70-03, there are several annexes which encapsulate specific usage patterns, maximum emission power and duty cycle requirements.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] In Europe, 863 to 870 MHz band has been allocated for license-free operation using FHSS, DSSS, or analog modulation with either a transmission duty cycle of 0.1%, 1% or 10% depending on the band, or Listen Before Talk (LBT) with Adaptive Frequency Agility (AFA).
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] Although this band falls under the Short Range Device umbrella, it is being used in Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN) wireless telecommunication networks, designed to allow long-range communications at a low bit rate among things (connected objects).
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] As of December 2011, unrestricted voice communications are allowed in the 869.7-870.0 MHz band with channel spacing of 25 kHz or less and maximum power output of 5 mW ERP.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] SRD860 handheld transceivers were briefly available in mid 2000s, however they did not offer dual-band compatibility with PMR446 and LPD433 bands.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] As of 2012, they have been put off-market.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] From January 2018, the four RFID frequencies are also available for data networks, with a power up to 500 mW and a bandwidth of 200 kHz.
[src:wireless-mbus/short-range-device] Specific restrictions on usage apply, such as a low duty cycle, LBT (listen before transmit) and APC (adaptive power control).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A **smart meter** is an electronic device that records information—such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor—and communicates the information to the consumer and electricity suppliers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) differs from automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The term *smart meter* often refers to an electricity meter, but it also may mean a device measuring natural gas, water or district heating consumption.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] More generally, a smart meter is an electronic device that records information such as consumption of electric energy, voltage levels, current, and power factor.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters communicate the information to the consumer for greater clarity of consumption behavior, and electricity suppliers for system monitoring and customer billing.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters typically record energy near real-time, and report regularly, in short intervals throughout the day.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters enable two-way communication between the meter and the central system.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters may be part of a *smart grid*, but do not themselves constitute a smart grid.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) differs from Automated Meter Reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communication between the meter and the supplier.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Communications from the meter to the network may be wireless, or via fixed wired connections such as power-line communication (PLC).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Similar meters, usually referred to as interval or time-of-use meters, have existed for years, but smart meters usually involve real-time or near real-time sensors, power outage notification, and power quality monitoring.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] These additional features are more than simple AMR.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] They are similar in many respects to AMI meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Interval and time-of-use meters historically have been installed to measure commercial and industrial customers, but may not have automatic reading.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Research by the UK consumer group, showed that as many as one in three confuse smart meters with energy monitors, also known as in-home display monitors.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 1972, Theodore Paraskevakos, while working with Boeing in Huntsville, Alabama, developed a sensor monitoring system that used digital transmission for security, fire, and medical alarm systems as well as meter reading capabilities.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This technology was a spin-off from the automatic telephone line identification system, now known as Caller ID.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 1977, he launched Metretek, Inc., which developed and produced the first smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The installed base of smart meters in Europe at the end of 2008 was about 39 million units, according to analyst firm Berg Insight.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Globally, Pike Research found that smart meter shipments were 17.4 million units for the first quarter of 2011.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Visiongain determined that the value of the global smart meter market would reach US$7 billion in 2012.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Tahir Mahmood, researchers of University of Engineering & Technology Taxila, Pakistan, introduced the concept of Smart Energy Meters in 2013.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] As of January 2018, over 99 million electricity meters were deployed across the European Union, with an estimated 24 million more to be installed by the end of 2020.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The European Commission DG Energy estimates the 2020 installed base to have required €18.8 billion in investment, growing to €40.7 billion by 2030, with a total deployment of 266 million smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] By the end of 2018, the U.S. had over 86 million smart meters installed.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 2017, there were 665 million smart meters installed globally.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Revenue generation is expected to grow from $12.8 billion in 2017 to $20 billion by 2022.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Since the inception of electricity deregulation and market-driven pricing throughout the world, utilities have been looking for a means to match consumption with generation.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Non-smart electrical and gas meters only measure total consumption, providing no information of when the energy was consumed.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters provide a way of measuring electricity consumption in near real-time.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This allows utility companies to charge different prices for consumption according to the time of day and the season.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It also facilitates more accurate cash-flow models for utilities.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Since smart meters can be read remotely, labor costs are reduced for utilities.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart metering offers potential benefits to customers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] With regards to consumption reduction, this is critical for understanding the benefits of smart meters because the relatively small percentage benefits in terms of savings are multiplied by millions of users.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters for water consumption can also provide detailed and timely information about customer water use and early notification of possible water leaks in their premises.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Electricity consumption, and hence pricing, usually peaks at certain predictable times of the day and the season.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In particular, if generation is constrained, prices can rise when power from other jurisdictions or more costly generation is brought online.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A 2013 academic study based on existing trials showed that homeowners' electricity consumption on average is reduced by approximately 3-5% when provided with real-time feedback.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Another advantage of smart meters that benefits both customers and the utility is the monitoring capability they provide for the whole electrical system.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] As part of an AMI, utilities can use the real-time data from smart meters measurements related to current, voltage, and power factor to detect system disruptions more quickly, allowing immediate corrective action to minimize customer impact such as blackouts.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters also help utilities understand the power grid needs with more granularity than legacy meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This greater understanding facilitates system planning to meet customer energy needs while reducing the likelihood of additional infrastructure investments, which eliminates unnecessary spending or energy cost increases.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] As a result, smart meters are considered an essential technology to the decarbonisation of the energy system.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Government agencies and utilities are turning toward advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) systems as part of larger "smart grid" initiatives.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] AMI extends automatic meter reading (AMR) technology by providing two-way meter communications, allowing commands to be sent toward the home for multiple purposes, including time-based pricing information, demand-response actions, or remote service disconnects.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Wireless technologies are critical elements of the neighborhood network, aggregating a mesh configuration of up to thousands of meters for back haul to the utility's IT headquarters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The network between the measurement devices and business systems allows the collection and distribution of information to customers, suppliers, utility companies, and service providers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This enables these businesses to participate in demand response services.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Consumers can use the information provided by the system to change their normal consumption patterns to take advantage of lower prices.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Pricing can be used to curb the growth of peak demand consumption.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] AMI differs from traditional automatic meter reading (AMR) in that it enables two-way communications with the meter.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Systems only capable of meter readings do not qualify as AMI systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Together, these components help utilities and consumers monitor and manage energy use efficiently, supporting smarter grid management.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Communication is a cornerstone of smart meter technology, enabling reliable and secure data transmission to central systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] However, the diversity of environments in which smart meters operate presents significant challenges.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] stands out among smart metering connectivity technologies because it leverages existing electrical power infrastructure for data transmission.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Unlike cellular, radio-frequency (RF), or Wi-Fi-based solutions, PLC does not require building or maintaining separate communication networks, making it inherently more cost-effective and easier to scale.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] G3-PLC supports IPv6-based communications and adaptive data rates, providing robust performance even in noisy environments, while PRIME (PoweRline Intelligent Metering Evolution) focuses on efficient, high-speed communication with low-cost implementation.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] like Europe, South America, and parts of Asia where dense infrastructure supports its use.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Utilities favor PLC for its reliability in urban environments and for connecting large numbers of meters within smart grid networks.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] An important feature of G3-PLC and PRIME is their ability to enable mesh networking (also called multi-hop), where smart meters act as repeaters for other meters in the network.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This functionality allows meters to relay data from neighboring meters to ensure that the information reaches the Data Concentrator Unit (DCU), even if direct communication is not possible due to distance or signal obstructions.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This approach enhances network reliability and coverage, particularly in dense urban environments or geographically challenging areas.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The challenges faced by rural utilities differ significantly from those of urban counterparts or utilities in remote, mountainous, or poorly serviced areas.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters often extend their functionality through integration into **Home Area Networks (HANs)**.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Technologies used in HANs vary globally but typically include PLC, wireless ad hoc networks, and Zigbee.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] By leveraging appropriate connectivity solutions, smart meters can address environmental and infrastructural needs while delivering communication and enhanced functionality.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Electricity smart meters start to be utilized as gateways for gas and water meters, creating integrated smart metering systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In this configuration, gas and water meters communicate with the electricity meter using Wireless M-Bus (Wireless Meter-Bus), a European standard (EN 13757-4) designed for secure and efficient data transmission between utility meters and data collectors.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The electricity meter then aggregates this data and transmits it to the central utility network via Power Line Communication (PLC), which leverages existing electrical wiring for data transfer.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meter communication protocols are essential for enabling reliable, efficient, and secure data exchange between meters, utilities, and other components of advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] These protocols address the diverse requirements of global markets, supporting various communication methods, from optical ports and serial connections to power line communication (PLC) and wireless networks.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Below is an overview of key protocols, including ANSI standards widely used in North America, IEC protocols prevalent in Europe, the globally recognized OSGP for smart grid applications, and the PLC-focused Meters and More, each designed to meet specific needs in energy monitoring and management.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] "IEC 62056 is the most widely adopted protocol" for smart meter communication, enabling reliable, two-way data exchange within Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It encompasses the DLMS/COSEM protocol for structuring and managing metering data.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] "It is widely used because of its flexibility, scalability, and ability to support different communication media such as Power Line Communication (PLC), TCP/IP, and wireless networks.".
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It also supports data transmission over serial connections using ASCII or binary formats, with physical media options such as modulated light (via LED and photodiode) or wired connections (typically EIA-485).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ANSI C12.18 is an ANSI Standard that describes a protocol used for two-way communications with a meter, mostly used in North American markets.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The C12.18 Standard is written specifically for meter communications via an ANSI Type 2 Optical Port, and specifies lower-level protocol details.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ANSI C12.19 specifies the data tables that are used.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ANSI C12.21 is an extension of C12.18 written for modem instead of optical communications, so it is better suited to automatic meter reading.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ANSI C12.22 is the communication protocol for remote communications.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The Open Smart Grid Protocol (OSGP) is a family of specifications published by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI) used in conjunction with the ISO/IEC 14908 control networking standard for smart metering and smart grid applications.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Millions of smart meters based on OSGP are deployed worldwide.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] On July 15, 2015, the OSGP Alliance announced the release of a new security protocol (OSGP-AES-128-PSK) and its availability from OSGP vendors.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This deprecated the original OSGP-RC4-PSK security protocol which had been identified to be vulnerable.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] "Meters and More was created in 2010 from the coordinated work between Enel and Endesa to adopt, maintain and evolve the field-proven Meters and More open communication protocol for smart grid solutions." .
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 2010, the Meters and More Association was established to promote the protocol globally, ensuring interoperability and efficiency in power line communication (PLC)-based smart metering systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Meters and More is an open communication protocol designed for advanced metering infrastructure (AMI).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It facilitates reliable, high-speed data exchange over PLC networks, focusing on energy monitoring, demand response, and secure two-way communication between utilities and consumers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Unlike DLMS/COSEM, which is a globally standardized and versatile protocol supporting multiple utilities (electricity, gas, and water), Meters and More is tailored specifically for PLC-based systems, emphasizing efficiency, reliability, and ease of deployment in electricity metering.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] There is a growing trend toward the use of TCP/IP technology as a common communication platform for Smart Meter applications, so that utilities can deploy multiple communication systems, while using IP technology as a common management platform.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A universal metering interface would allow for development and mass production of smart meters and smart grid devices prior to the communication standards being set, and then for the relevant communication modules to be easily added or switched when they are.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This would lower the risk of investing in the wrong standard as well as permit a single product to be used globally even if regional communication standards vary.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI), the server infrastructure is crucial for managing, storing, and processing the large volumes of data generated by smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This infrastructure ensures seamless communication between smart meters, utility providers, and end-users, supporting real-time monitoring, billing, and grid management.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A Data Concentrator Unit (DCU) aggregates data from multiple smart meters within a localized area (e.g., a neighborhood or building) before transmitting it to the central server.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Data concentrators reduce the communication load on the network and help overcome connectivity challenges by acting as intermediaries between smart meters and the head-end system (HES).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The HES is responsible for collecting, validating, and managing data received from data concentrators and smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It serves as the central communication hub, facilitating two-way communication between the smart meters and the utility's central servers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The HES supports meter configuration, firmware updates, and real-time data retrieval, ensuring data integrity and security.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] is a specialized software platform that stores and processes large volumes of meter data collected by the HES.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Key functions of the MDMS include data validation, estimation, and editing, as well as billing preparation, load analysis, and anomaly detection.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ), and demand response systems, to enable efficient energy management.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Data analytics for smart meters leverages machine learning to extract insights from energy consumption data.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Key applications include demand forecasting, dynamic pricing, Energy Disaggregation, and fault detection, enabling optimized grid performance and personalized energy management.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] These techniques drive efficiency, cost savings, and sustainability in modern energy systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] "Energy Disaggregation, or the breakdown of your energy use based on specific appliances or devices", is an exploratory technique for analyzing energy consumption in households, commercial buildings, and industrial settings.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] By using data from a single energy meter, it employs algorithms and machine learning to estimate individual appliance usage without separate monitors.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Known as Non-Intrusive Load Monitoring (NILM), this emerging method offers insights into energy efficiency, helping users optimize usage and reduce costs.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] While promising, energy disaggregation is still being refined for accuracy and scalability as part of smart energy management innovations.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The other critical technology for smart meter systems is the information technology at the utility that integrates the Smart Meter networks with utility applications, such as billing and CIS.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This includes the Meter Data Management system.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It also is essential for smart grid implementations that power line communication (PLC) technologies used within the home over a Home Area Network (HAN), are standardized and compatible.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The HAN allows HVAC systems and other household appliances to communicate with the smart meter, and from there to the utility.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Currently there are several broadband or narrowband standards in place, or being developed, that are not yet compatible.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] To address this issue in the United States, the National Institute for Standards and Technology (NIST) established the PAP15 group, which studies and recommends coexistence mechanisms with a focus on the harmonization of PLC Standards for the HAN.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The objective of the group is to ensure that all PLC technologies selected for the HAN coexist as a minimum.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The two leading broadband PLC technologies selected are the HomePlug AV / IEEE 1901 and ITU-T G.hn technologies.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Technical working groups within these organizations are working to develop appropriate coexistence mechanisms.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The HomePlug Powerline Alliance has developed a new standard for smart grid HAN communications called the HomePlug Green PHY specification.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It is interoperable and coexistent with the widely deployed HomePlug AV technology and with the latest IEEE 1901 global Standard and is based on Broadband OFDM technology.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] ITU-T commissioned in 2010 a new project called G.hnem, to address the home networking aspects of energy management, built upon existing Low Frequency Narrowband OFDM technologies.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Some groups have expressed concerns regarding the cost, health, fire risk, security and privacy effects of smart meters and the remote controllable "kill switch" that is included with most of them.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Many of these concerns regard wireless-only smart meters with no home energy monitoring or control or safety features.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Metering-only solutions, while popular with utilities because they fit existing business models and have cheap up-front capital costs, often result in such "backlash".
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Often the entire smart grid and smart building concept is discredited in part by confusion about the difference between home control and home area network technology and AMI.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The (now former) attorney general of Connecticut has stated that he does not believe smart meters provide any financial benefit to consumers, however, the cost of the installation of the new system is absorbed by those customers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters expose the power grid to cyberattacks that could lead to power outages, both by cutting off people's electricity and by overloading the grid.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] However many cybersecurity experts state that smart meters of the UK and Germany have relatively high cybersecurity and that any such attack there would thus require extraordinarily high efforts or financial resources.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The EU Cybersecurity Act took effect in June 2019, which includes Directive on Security Network and Information Systems establishing notification and security requirements for operators of essential services.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Through the Smartgrid Cybersecurity Committee, the U.S.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Department of Energy published cybersecurity guidelines for grid operators in 2010 and updated them in 2014.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Implementing security protocols that protect these devices from malicious attacks has been problematic, due to their limited computational resources and long operational life.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The current version of IEC 62056 includes the possibility to encrypt, authenticate, or sign the meter data.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] One proposed smart meter data verification method involves analyzing the network traffic in real-time to detect anomalies using an Intrusion Detection System (IDS).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] By identifying exploits as they are being leveraged by attackers, an IDS mitigates the suppliers' risks of energy theft by consumers and denial-of-service attacks by hackers.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Energy utilities must choose between a centralized IDS, embedded IDS, or dedicated IDS depending on the individual needs of the utility.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Researchers have found that for a typical advanced metering infrastructure, the centralized IDS architecture is superior in terms of cost efficiency and security gains.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In the United Kingdom, the Data Communication Company, which transports the commands from the supplier to the smart meter, performs an additional anomaly check on commands issued (and signed) by the energy supplier.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] According to a report published by Brian Krebs, in 2009 a Puerto Rico electricity supplier asked the FBI to investigate large-scale thefts of electricity related to its smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The FBI found that former employees of the power company and the company that made the meters were being paid by consumers to reprogram the devices to show incorrect results, as well as teaching people how to do it themselves.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Several hacking tools that allow security researchers and penetration testers verify the security of electric utility smart meters have been released so far.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Most health concerns about the meters arise from the pulsed radiofrequency (RF) radiation emitted by wireless smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Members of the California State Assembly asked the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST) to study the issue of potential health impacts from smart meters, in particular whether current FCC standards are protective of public health.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The CCST report in April 2011 found no health impacts, based both on lack of scientific evidence of harmful effects from radio frequency (RF) waves and that the RF exposure of people in their homes to smart meters is likely to be minuscule compared to RF exposure to cell phones and microwave ovens.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Daniel Hirsch, retired director of the Program on Environmental and Nuclear Policy at UC Santa Cruz, criticized the CCST report on the grounds that it did not consider studies that suggest the potential for non-thermal health effects such as latent cancers from RF exposure.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has adopted recommended Permissible Exposure Limit (PEL) for all RF transmitters (including smart meters) operating at frequencies of 300 kHz to 100 GHz.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] These limits, based on field strength and power density, are below the levels of RF radiation that are hazardous to human health.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Other studies substantiate the finding of the California Council on Science and Technology (CCST).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 2011, the Electric Power Research Institute performed a study to gauge human exposure to smart meters as compared to the FCC PEL.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The report found that most smart meters only transmit RF signals 1% of the time or less.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] At this rate, and at a distance of 1 foot from the meter, RF exposure would be at a rate of 0.14% of the FCC PEL.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] An indirect potential for harm to health by smart meters is that they enable energy companies to disconnect consumers remotely, typically in response to difficulties with payment.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This can cause health problems to vulnerable people in financial difficulty; in addition to denial of heat, lighting, and use of appliances, there are people who depend on power to use medical equipment essential for life.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] While there may be legal protections in place to protect the vulnerable, many people in the UK were disconnected in violation of the rules.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Issues surrounding smart meters causing fires have been reported, particularly involving the manufacturer Sensus.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] PECO Energy Company replaced the Sensus meters it had deployed in the Philadelphia, US region after reports that a number of the units had overheated and caused fires.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In July 2014, SaskPower, the province-run utility company of the Canadian province of Saskatchewan, halted its roll-out of Sensus meters after similar, isolated incidents were discovered.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Shortly afterward, Portland General Electric announced that it would replace 70,000 smart meters that had been deployed in the state of Oregon after similar reports.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The company noted that it had been aware of the issues since at least 2013, and they were limited to specific models it had installed between 2010 and 2012.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] On July 30, 2014, after a total of eight recent fire incidents involving the meters, SaskPower was ordered by the Government of Saskatchewan to immediately end its smart meter program, and remove the 105,000 smart meters it had installed.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] One technical reason for privacy concerns is that these meters send detailed information about how much electricity is being used each time.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] More frequent reports provide more detailed information.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Infrequent reports may be of little benefit for the provider, as it doesn't allow as good demand management in the response of changing needs for electricity.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] On the other hand, widespread reports would allow the utility company to infer behavioral patterns for the occupants of a house, such as when the members of the household are probably asleep or absent.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Furthermore, the fine-grained information collected by smart meters raises growing concerns of privacy invasion due to personal behavior exposure (private activity, daily routine, etc.).
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Current trends are to increase the frequency of reports.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A solution that benefits both provider and user privacy would be to adapt the interval dynamically.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Another solution involves energy storage installed at the household used to reshape the energy consumption profile.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In British Columbia the electric utility is government-owned and as such must comply with privacy laws that prevent the sale of data collected by smart meters; many parts of the world are serviced by private companies that are able to sell their data.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In Australia debt collectors can make use of the data to know when people are at home.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Used as evidence in a court case in Austin, Texas, police agencies secretly collected smart meter power usage data from thousands of residences to determine which used more power than "typical" to identify marijuana growing operations.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meter power data usage patterns can reveal much more than how much power is being used.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Research has demonstrated that smart meters sampling power levels at two-second intervals can reliably identify when different electrical devices are in use.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Reviews of smart meter programs, moratoriums, delays, and "opt-out" programs are some responses to the concerns of customers and government officials.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In response to residents who did not want a smart meter, in June 2012 a utility in Hawaii changed its smart meter program to "opt out".
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The utility said that once the smart grid installation project is nearing completion, KIUC may convert the deferral policy to an opt-out policy or program and may charge a fee to those members to cover the costs of servicing the traditional meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Any fee would require approval from the Hawaii Public Utilities Commission.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] After receiving numerous complaints about health, hacking, and privacy concerns with the wireless digital devices, the Public Utility Commission of the US state of Maine voted to allow customers to opt-out of the meter change at the cost of $12 a month.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In Connecticut, another US state to consider smart metering, regulators declined a request by the state's largest utility, Connecticut Light & Power, to install 1.2 million of the devices, arguing that the potential savings in electric bills do not justify the cost.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] CL&P already offers its customers time-based rates.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The state's Attorney General George Jepsen was quoted as saying the proposal would cause customers to spend upwards of $500 million on meters and get few benefits in return, a claim that Connecticut Light & Power disputed.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters allow dynamic pricing; it has been pointed out that, while this allows prices to be reduced at times of low demand, it can also be used to increase prices at peak times if all consumers have smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Additionally smart meters allow energy suppliers to switch customers to expensive prepay tariffs instantly in case of difficulties paying.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In the UK during a period of very high energy prices from 2021, companies were remotely switching smart meters from a credit tariff to an expensive prepay tariff which disconnects supplies unless credit has been purchased.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] While regulations do not permit this without appropriate precautions to help those in financial difficulties and to protect the vulnerable, the rules were often flouted.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] There are questions about whether electricity is or should be primarily a "when you need it" service where the inconvenience/cost-benefit ratio of time-shifting of loads is poor.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In the Chicago area, Commonwealth Edison ran a test installing smart meters on 8,000 randomly selected households together with variable rates and rebates to encourage cutting back during peak usage.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In *Crain's Chicago Business* article "Smart grid test underwhelms.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In the pilot, few power down to save money.", it was reported that fewer than 9% exhibited any amount of peak usage reduction and that the overall amount of reduction was "statistically insignificant".
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] This was from a report by the Electric Power Research Institute, a utility industry think tank who conducted the study and prepared the report.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] By 2016, the 7 million smart meters in Texas had not persuaded many people to check their energy data as the process was too complicated.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A report from a parliamentary group in the UK suggests people who have smart meters installed are expected to save an average of £11 annually on their energy bills, much less than originally hoped.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The 2016 cost-benefit analysis was updated in 2019 and estimated a similar average saving.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The Australian Victorian Auditor-General found in 2015 that 'Victoria's electricity consumers will have paid an estimated $2.239 billion for metering services, including the rollout and connection of smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Smart meters can allow real-time pricing, and in theory this could help smooth power consumption as consumers adjust their demand in response to price changes.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In 2013, *Take Back Your Power*, an independent Canadian documentary directed by Josh del Sol was released describing "dirty electricity" and the aforementioned issues with smart meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The film explores the various contexts of the health, legal, and economic concerns.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It features narration from the mayor of Peterborough, Ontario, Daryl Bennett, as well as American researcher De-Kun Li, journalist Blake Levitt, and Dr.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] It won a Leo Award for best feature-length documentary and the Annual Humanitarian Award from Indie Fest the following year.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Citizens Advice said in August 2018 that 80% of people with smart meters were happy with them.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Still, it had 3,000 calls in 2017 about problems.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] These related to first-generation smart meters losing their functionality, aggressive sales practices, and still having to send smart meter readings.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Ross Anderson of the Foundation for Information Policy Research has criticised the UK's program on the grounds that it is unlikely to lower energy consumption, is rushed and expensive, and does not promote metering competition.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The high number of SMETS1 meters installed has been criticized by Peter Earl, head of energy at the price comparison website comparethemarket.com.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] UK smart meters in southern England and the Midlands use the mobile phone network to communicate, so they do not work correctly when phone coverage is weak.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] A solution has been proposed, but was not operational as of March 2017.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In March 2018 the National Audit Office (NAO), which watches over public spending, opened an investigation into the smart meter program, which had cost £11bn by then, paid for by electricity users through higher bills.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The National Audit Office published the findings of its investigation in a report titled "Rolling out smart meters" published in November 2018.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The report, amongst other findings, indicated that the number of smart meters installed in the UK would fall materially short of the Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy (BEIS) original ambitions of all UK consumers having a smart meter installed by 2020.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] In September 2019, smart meter rollout in the UK was delayed for four years.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] Ross Anderson and Alex Henney wrote that "Ed Miliband cooked the books" to make a case for smart meters appear economically viable.
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] They say that the first three cost-benefit analyses of residential smart meters found that it would cost more than it would save, but "ministers kept on trying until they got a positive result...
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] To achieve 'profitability' the previous government stretched the assumptions shamelessly".
[src:wireless-mbus/smart-meter] The Employment Appeal Tribunal found that the law was in contravention of the European Convention on Human Rights.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:wireless-mbus/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Sub-metering may also refer to the monitoring of the electrical consumption of individual equipment within a building, such as HVAC, indoor and outdoor lighting, refrigeration, kitchen equipment and more.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Typically a multi-tenant dwelling has either one master meter for the entire property or a meter for each building and the property is responsible for the entire utility bill.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Submetering allows property owners who supply utilities to their tenants the ability to account for each tenant's usage in measurable terms.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] By fairly billing each tenant for their portion, submetering promotes conservation and offsets the expense of bills generated from a master meter, maintenance and improvements for well water systems, lagoon, or septic systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Submetering is legally allowable in most states and municipalities, but owners should consult a Utility Management Vendor for assistance with local and state compliance and regulations.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Typical users of submetering are mobile home parks, apartments, condominiums, townhouses, student housing, and commercial areas.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Usually, utility submetering is placed in situations where the local utility cannot or will not individually meter the utility in question.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Municipal Utility companies are often reluctant to take on metering individual spaces for several reasons.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] One reason is that rental space tenants tend to be more transient and are more difficult to collect from.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] By billing only the owner, they can place liens on real property if not paid (as opposed to tenants they may not know exist or who have little to lose if they move without paying).
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Utilities also generally prefer not to have water meters beyond their easement (i.e., the property boundary), since leaks to a service line would be before the meter and could be of less concern to a property owner.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Other reasons include difficulty in getting access to meters for reading, or electrical systems and plumbing not suitable for submetering.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Before submetering, many landlords either included the utility cost in the bulk price of the rent or lease, or divided the utility usage among the tenants in some way such as equally, by square footage via allocation methods often called RUBS (Ratio Utility Billing System) or some other means.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Without a meter to measure individual usage, there is less incentive to identify building inefficiencies, since the other tenants or landlord may pay all or part of those costs.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Submetering creates awareness of water and Energy conservation because landlords and tenants are equally aware of what they will pay for these inefficiencies if they are not attended to.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Conservation also allows property owners to keep the cost of rent reasonable and fair for all units regardless of how much water or energy they consume.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] On the other hand, submetering provides an opportunity for building owners to shift their rising electricity costs to tenants who lack ownership or control over thermal efficiency of the structure, its insulation, windows, and major energy consuming appliances.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Landlords may attempt to deem their charges for electric service as "additional rent" making tenants subject to eviction for nonpayment of electric bills, which would not be possible if they were direct customers of the utility.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The Ontario Energy Board in August 2009 nullified all landlord submetering and allowed future submetering only upon informed tenant consent, including provision of third party energy audits to tenants to enable them to judge the total cost of rent plus electricity.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Some submetering products connect with software that provides consumption data.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] This data provides users with the information to locate leaks and high-consumption areas.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Users can apply this data to implement conservation or renovation projects to lower usage & costs, meet government mandates, or participate in green building programs such as LEED and green globes.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] A submetering system typically includes a "master meter", which is owned by the utility supplying the water, electricity, or gas, with overall usage billed directly to the property owner.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The property owner or manager then places their own private meters on individual tenant spaces to determine individual usage levels and bill each tenant for their share.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] In some cases, the landlord might add the usage cost to the regular rent or lease bill.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] In other cases, a third party might read, bill, and possibly even collect for the service.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Some of these companies also install and maintain meters and reading systems.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Panel or circuit submeters are used to measure resource use of the same system for added security, economic, reliability, and behavioral benefits.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] These provide important insights into resource consumption of building systems and equipment working in the same series.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Submeters can measure use of a single panel, or multiple points within a panel system using single-point, multi-point, and branch circuit submeters.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The latest trend in submetering is Automatic Meter Reading, or AMR.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] This technology is used to get from meter reading to billing by an automated electronic means.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] This can be by handheld computers that collect data using touch wands, walk or drive-by radio, fixed network systems where the meter has a transmitter or transceiver that sends the data to a central location, or transmission via Wi-Fi, cellular, or Internet connections.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Although not technically submetering, an alternate method of utility cost allocation called RUBS (Ratio Utility Billing Systems) is sometimes used to allocate costs to tenants when true submetering is not practical or not possible due to plumbing or wiring constraints.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] This method divides utility costs by square footage, number of occupants, or some other combination of cost ratios.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] For example, central heating in apartment blocks in Belgium, Germany and Switzerland is sometimes submetered with liquid filled calibrated vials, known as heat cost allocators, attached to each of the heating radiators.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The metering company visits the apartments about once a year and reads the liquid level and replaces the vials.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Some apartment owners have replaced the vials with electronic submeters that transmit temperature readings via radio to a master unit in each apartment.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The master unit in turn transmits collated readings to the utility company, thereby saving both labour costs and inconvenience to both tenant and landlord.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The master unit displays a number representing the current total of "heating value".
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The concept of submetering was effectively "invented" sometime in the 1920s, when many laws currently affecting submetering were written.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Submetering was not widespread until the energy crisis in the mid-1970s, which prompted an increase in submetering for gas and electric usage.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Water submetering began its increase nationally in the mid-1990s when water and wastewater prices started rising.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] However, submetering really did not take a hold in the property management world until the late 1980s, with the ever increasing costs associated with utilities and a society more aware of environmental conservation.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] Utility submetering has its roots in Denmark.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] In 1902 two Danish brothers, Axel and Odin Clorius, established Clorius Controls.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The company commenced work on developing and producing a range of self-acting temperature controllers.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] In 1924 Clorius received its first patent for a heat cost allocator.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The device was meant to measure energy usage in apartments built with a common boiler heating system.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] The device was attached to each radiator in an apartment unit.
[src:wireless-mbus/utility-submeter] By measuring energy usage at each radiator, a consumption-based utility bill could be prepared for each unit.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The M-Bus was developed to fill the need for a system for the networking and remote reading of utility meters, for example to measure the consumption of gas or water in the home.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] This bus fulfills the special requirements of remotely powered or battery-driven systems, including consumer utility meters.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] When interrogated, the meters deliver the data they have collected to a common master, such as a hand-held computer, connected at periodic intervals to read all utility meters of a building.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] An alternative method of collecting data centrally is to transmit meter readings via a modem.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Other applications for the M-Bus such as alarm systems, flexible illumination installations, heating control, etc. are suitable.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Since no bus system was available for the requirements of meter reading, the M-Bus was developed by Horst Ziegler of the University of Paderborn in cooperation with Texas Instruments Deutschland GmbH and Techem GmbH.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The concept was based on the ISO-OSI Reference Model, in order to realize an open system which could use almost any desired protocol.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Since the M-Bus is not a network, and therefore does not – among other things – need a transport or session layer, the levels four to six of the OSI model are empty.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Therefore, only the physical, the data link, the network and the application layer are provided with functions.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] M-Bus connection is called M-Bus or HAN (Home Area Network) consumer connection.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] M-Bus uses two-wire telephone cable (JYStY 1x*2x*0.8 mm or similar, 73 ohm/km, 120 nF/km) maximum length of 350 meters when using nominal transfer speeds 300 and 9600 baud.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Lowering the speed up to 1000 meter cable can be used.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] There is no standardized connector, but RJ11 and RJ12 Modular connectors are used by meter manufacturers.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The master communication uses voltage signaling, where 1 (idle state, mark) is the bus nominal 36 volts, 0 (space) drops the voltage to 24 volts (V).
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] As bus voltage can vary with length and load, the signal is specified as 1 for bus voltage drop less than 5.5 V, 0 for drop higher than 8.2 V.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Slaves communicate by current consumption, where 1 (idle state, mark) is less than 1.5 milliamperes (mA), 0 (space) raises current to 11–20 mA.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The signal is specified as the at least 11 mA current increase.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The slaves are connected via diode bridge and can use either polarity of the wires.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] To protect the bus against shortcircuited slaves, a 430 ohm is connected in series at each slave (or, two 215 ohm resistors, one for each wire).
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Most slaves use at most this, some can need two units (3 mA).
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Masters can provide type-dependent number of load units, and usually visually indicate overload.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The data link protocol is described by IEC 870-5, or its updated version, IEC 60870-5.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The data are sent in serial form, at speed between 300 and 9600 bit/s (some variants may operate up to 19200 or 38400 bit/s), using one start bit, one stop bit, and even parity (8e1).
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] The least significant bit is sent first.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] When sending packets ("telegrams"), there is no pause between stop and subsequent start bit.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Suggested speeds are 300, 2400, 9600, and with newer hardware 38400 bit/s, while 2400 bit/s is most common.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Devices with different baudrates can coexist on the same bus.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Some devices use Automatic Baud Rate Detection (ABR) or autobauding.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] CI-field is the control information field.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Length field in control/long frame is sent twice.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Minimum value is 0x03, as C-field, A-field and CI-field are mandatory parts of the payload.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Slaves respond only to correctly formed packets that match their address.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Any fault is indicated by lack of response.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Absence of response is defined as no response for 330 bit periods (35 ms for 9600 bit/s, 1.1 s for 300 bit/s) plus 50 ms.
[src:wireless-mbus/wireless-m-bus] Numerical values are usually sent in BCD format.
